Xpath : Xpath is selenium locator to identify any element with the help html DOM.

1. Absolute Xpath: Follow entire dom structure to identify the element.
        e.g. /html/body/div/div[1]/div/div[1]/div/div[2]/div[2]/form/div[1]/div/div[2]/input


2. Relative Xpath: Relative xpath identify the element with the help of element attribute.
        e.g. //tagname[@attribute='value'] | //*[@attribute='value']
         ->  //input[@placeholder="Username"]  |  //*[@placeholder="Username"]



         // If multiple elements are matching with the same property, than we use indexing
            e.g. -> (//input[@id="firstname"])[1]



BASIC XPath Methods:

1. Text Method.  : identify the element with the help elements Text
                    e.g.  //tagname[text()='text value']
                    -> //td[text()='Pune']
                    -> //a[text()='Tutorials']
                    -> //td[text()='6004']


2. Contains Method. : identify the element with PARTIAL atribute value or PARTIAL text value.

                i). Partial Atribute value : //tagname[contains(@attribute, 'attribute value')]

                                             -> //input[contains(@id, 't_address1')]

                ii). Partial Text value : //tagname[contains(text(), 'text value)]
                                            -> //span[contains(text(), ' application – $200')] 
                                            -> //h1[contains(text(), 'Dummy Booking')]



3. normalize space methode:  this method ignores all unnecessary space in atribute name.
                            -> //tagname[normalize-space()='value']
                            -> //button[normalize-space()='Login']



